In economics, history offers few indications of time frame.
After the first rate hike, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The aggressiveness of the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That’s why U.S. central bank officials have so strongly emphasized that investors should focus not on when the interest rate starts to rise but on the trajectory of the time it takes to normalize.
In fact, there are multiple variables in the game.
However, in the end, market players may find that all the turmoil related to the interest rate increase has been exaggerated.
“The first rate hike decided by the Fed after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the era of ‘cheap money,’” Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a note to clients.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of US interest rates to more normal but still low levels to constitute the seismic shock that everyone seems to be afraid of.
However, it cannot be said that there will be no effects.
Here’s how some sectors of the economy might react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation the market has faced in recent months, anticipating an increase in the interest rate can volatilize things for a while.
However, at the moment of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
