Recession is a reality of economic life, but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In the current situation, the Fed is facing conditions that have not existed before and could accelerate a recession.
Specifically, the gross domestic product will approach its historic low point for an increase in the Fed interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was less than 4.5%.
Although in the second quarter of 2015, the figure was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, with the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Rising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and raise the question “whether it’s different this time around,” Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing all year for a growth decision from the Fed, with all eyes set on this week’s Federal Open Market Commission meeting, which ends on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists are of the opinion that the FOMC could approve an increase in the interest rate on the occasion of this meeting, futures transactions indicate a probability of only 25%.
