Advantages and Disadvantages of Converting Credits to Swiss Francs
On the banking market, two offers have already appeared for the conversion of loans in Swiss francs in lei, the main advantages being the exclusion of currency risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come in a few years, when the variable interest rate can lead to higher rates.
Banca Transilvania has just completed the process of converting the loans in francs granted by Volksbank, and Bancpost has announced the conversion offer for its own customers.
According to the data compiled by analysts of the financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest at lei, 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, Transylvania Bank’s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of customers with loans in francs due to two successive reductions: the balance with the value of risk and administration fees paid by the customer was reduced, then an additional reduction of 22.5% was applied to the balance in lei.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to how much they paid monthly equivalent in lei before conversion.
Thus, Banca Transilvania reduces the rate by 42.5%, and Bancpost, by 33% in the first three years and, theoretically, by 18% in the following years.
Benefit
The main advantage of borrowing in lei in CHF is that the foreign exchange risk is eliminated, the consumer being protected from future increases in the franc, and the repayment of the loan will be made in the currency in which he receives his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that no property revaluation is done, no additional guarantees are required, and another proof of income is required.
In practice, no new financial and legal analysis of the loan will be made, nor will there be additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Also, both banks offer discounts at the monthly rate, compared to what customers paid before conversion, equivalent to lei.
Risks
The problem is that the rate in the first few years is more of the interest, and the client repays very little of the principal.
Bancpost’s offer with a very low interest rate in the first three years seems advantageous for customers.
However, it is not known how this interest will evolve after three years.
The margin offered to customers can be greater than 3.25%, so overall, and the cost reduction is lower.
A possible risk for all loans in lei with variable interest is that the ROBOR index will increase significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor - CHF index).
