On the occasion of the most anticipated meeting in recent years, policy makers from the Federal Reserve will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahogany table to decide if the time has come to raise a key interest rate for the first time in nearly a decade.
Above them, at the end of the central bank’s meeting room, a mural of the United States will be seen.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, President of the Fed, and his colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation above all else.
The Central Bank has received a double task from Congress: to maximize the employment rate in the U.S. and to maintain price stability.
But since the great economic crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is an unwritten third task: financial stability.
And this third task could be factor X in an overly difficult-to-predict decision to be announced on Tuesday, which will determine whether the U.S. economy is prepared to be challenged by the unprecedented stimulus offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in force since the end of 2008.
Even if most of the data indicates a strong growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare already cautious Fed officials away from adding volatility by raising the benchmark rate to federal funds – even by just a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation will be the first and main issues they will pursue,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise the interest rate, the growing uncertainty in the global market is enough to give them arguments to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the decision the Fed will make, which in itself causes instability in the financial market.
About half of the economists surveyed by Bloomberg recently anticipated an interest rate hike this week.
But financial markets are expecting the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30%.
This would indicate a fall on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policymakers mitigate the blow by promising it would take a long time until the next hike.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average climbed 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16,599.85.
The surge was triggered by expectations that the Fed’s decision-makers will keep the interest rate stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising for the Fed to raise interest rates at this time,” Lonski said.
If the Fed’s decision-makers were to do so, they “should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic on the financial markets.”
Other experts said an increase in the interest rate would calm the financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the Fed would act.
Just a month ago, the Fed appeared to be about to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards a slow tightening of monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the US recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that he expected an interest rate hike this year despite objections from liberals that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth was solid this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest percentage in more than seven years and close to the level the Fed considers total employment.
Salary gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to fall short of the central bank’s annual target, Fed decision makers said a key reason was the temporary effect of falling oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates and needs them, given the pressure on the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began firing at the end of this month, after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones industrial average fell 16% below its record high in May, as investors feared the slowdown in China’s economy would slow global growth.
The market fell somewhat this month, with the Dow index now about 10% below its May peak.
For the Fed decision-makers, market agitation is added to the complex calculation of the moment of interest rate increase.
“Without what has happened in the financial markets and the news of the weakening of the Chinese economy in recent weeks, they would have been firmer at the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at the UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and formerly the Fed official.
Now, he anticipates that they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy and there is hardly any data to be based on subsequent events in China,” Oliner said.
The welfare of the global economy is not one of the major interests of the Fed, so it should practically not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the central bank’s influence has been enormous.
The simple allusion of then-president Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “close” its monetary expansion has triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, Fed officials are expected not only to monitor progress in other areas, but also to consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the world economy.
His decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at Envestnet Inc.’s wealth management firm.
Jeffrey Lacker, president of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Va., said this month that “the Fed has an oversized track record of reacting to changes in the financial market that seem to have nothing to do with economic fundamentals.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that supported the interest rate hike, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that has affected Asia has led the Fed to reduce the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the limited-identification implications for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, Fed officials reverted to the declines.
The Fed should put the issue of financial stability first only in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate commission.
The last turbulent period does not rise far to that level, he said.
“We certainly don’t want to get into the situation of fearing an increase in the interest rate because the markets have been upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still has the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until something changes in that regard, I don’t think it should be taken prematurely.
