Weight-loss surgery could be useful in diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight reduction surgery in people with mild obesity, with type 2 diabetes, could last for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say if diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those who follow non-surgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Surgery for weight loss, also called bariatric surgery, uses various methods to narrow the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of weight in relation to height, is considered normal in the range of 18.5-24.9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by going to: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery — gastric bypass and sleeve gastrectomy — in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI in those who underwent surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in the study.
Meanwhile, BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments for diabetes remained almost at the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured at 36% and partially at 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the mean level of hemoglobin A1c decreased from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the group treated with medical methods, it was maintained at about 8%.
But this improved “glycemic control” — reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels — did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the gastrectomy group in the sleeve, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 kg vs 14.2 kg), experienced more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 % vs 5.1) and high haemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1% haemoglobin A1c).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on heavyweight people in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, from the University of Arizona’s Phoenix School of Medicine.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery were about 29% less likely to die after 15 years, compared with a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who had undergone surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic view for people with BMI under 35 who are interested in the procedure.
“This is the point where this paper is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should begin to take the weight seriously when the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long for people to take this seriously,” she said.
I think once they’ve accumulated these genetic changes that have short-circuited their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it’s extremely hard to get back to normal.
