Hand washes with the aroma of strawberries, grapes, oranges are the most attractive for children.
Hand wash contains about 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, only a few swallows can cause alcohol poisoning.
“It’s very concentrated alcohol,” Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the Kansas University Hospital anti-poisoning center, told Fox Channel 4 in Kansas City.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones get to them, this is a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four strawberry-flavoured hand-washing sprays at school, arrived at the emergency room to receive treatment.
