Zuckerberg has mentioned that he wants to avoid the moments when someone posts on the account or an important event in life, and someone else will give "Dislike".
Users of the network, which has reached 1.5 billion active accounts, have long asked to have the opportunity to express their negative emotions or empathy with something sad.
Mark Zuckerberg also said that it is not very comfortable for people to give “likes” to current events, such as the refugee crisis, or in the event of the death of a family member.
“You may not feel comfortable giving like that post,” the Facebook representative pointed out.
A new button on Facebook has not been well received by everyone.
“There’s already enough hate on Facebook and social media,” said Afghanistan’s Atiq Haneef on the New York Times’ Facebook page, where the article on the subject was posted.
"I'm going to give 'Dislike' to the 'Dislike' button," he said.
Roger Anderson, a microbiologist from Atlanta, said there was nothing wrong with this button, encouraging people to have different opinions on Facebook.
Debra Aho Williamson, a social media analyst at eMarketer, said it’s hard to imagine that a single button can convey a complex range of negative emotions.
Moreover, she argues, the election campaign in America is approaching, and the "Dislike" button would create a total disaster.
