Corbyn, Brexit and the future of Europe
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have enjoyed over the past decades cannot continue in the years to come.
Until Saturday, few people in Romania probably knew who Jeremy Corbyn was.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the Labour Party in the UK, many are wondering to what extent the choice of a politician who, after all, is not in a decision-making position can affect us.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical leftist leader of the post-war Labour Party.
Declared Marxist, anti-monarchist (at one point asked Tony Blair, then prime minister, to remove the royal family from Buckingam Palace), a ferocious anti-American and a sympathizer of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on the political events by the British television channel "Himbolsh as he miesia" and "Himbolsh as he is today").
For Corbyn, who at the time considered the killing of Osama bin Laden a real tragedy, ISIS is almost preferred by the United States.
Following the pattern of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
Things like what Tsipras said and promised in Greece until he gave up on the real world and economic legitimacy.
The economic program of the new Labour leader envisages, among other things, massive renationalizations and printing money as a solution for financing development projects and covering very generous social benefits.
Of course, some might wonder why the money printing solution is not unanimously adopted around the world, we would then have a global overall prosperity!, but who would prevent such details?
Of course, we can charge blood to the bankers, become a kind of enemy of the left, but from what has been seen so many times in the past, not only in the former communist states or in Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of the mandates of Mitterrand and Hollande.
The extra money is quickly swallowed up by generous, uncovered promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher once said, “The problem with socialism is that at some point other people’s money runs out.”
Few give Jeremy Corbyn a real chance to ever become prime minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was not as extreme in beliefs as the party's fresh leader, failed lamentably in the election.
And then there was still in Britain a working class, in the classical sense of the word, relatively consistent and structured.
And the unions were much more influential than they are now.
Under the conditions of the new industrial landscape, in which services are dominant in the overall workforce, and extensive automation has made the industry massively in need of highly skilled workers, Corbyn’s rhetoric has a limited appeal.
But even from the opposition, it can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes Corbyn’s election increases the chances of Brexit, or Britain’s exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country’s membership in the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that has imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine these kinds of ideas with those expressed by the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric and you look at the refugee crisis shaking from the foundations of the EU you get to an explosive mix.
And not just for the UK.
But if the British decide after the referendum, which was to take place by 2017, to leave the Union the loss of capital symbolic for the whole European project and the deep bankruptcies created within it by the Euro crisis and now the refugees, between North and South, between East and West, leave room for the most worrying scenarios.
The more so for a whole series of member states, London was a counterweight to the Franco-German axis (in which anyway Berlin became increasingly the dominant actor).
It is true, the British business environment, the City, are strong advocates of the country’s stay in the EU.
Today’s Europe is no longer the past.
There are many resentments, which increase in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, as we have only recently seen in Jean Clude Junker's speech, tends increasingly to make major decisions over the heads of the vast majority of Member States by consulting only a few European powers, mainly Germany.
And this is happening as electoral support for anti-system, anti-immigration and Eurosceptic formations is growing dramatically across the continent.
In other words, the negatively charged emotional climate has reached higher levels than ever before.
This is the conclusion that the Financial Times draws when assessing the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation starting from the national interest.
If voters make the brain decision, then the UK will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn’s victory reminds us of the power of emotion in current politics.
However, Eastern Europe can be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as expected, we are witnessing a more pronounced integration of the euro area, which will push most of the countries in the region and to the periphery of interest and that of the decision-making process in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States feed their populist rhetoric from the frustrations accumulated in Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity that they have enjoyed in the last decades, the generous social benefits, can no longer continue in the following years.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Euro-immigration zone, both provoked by hasty decisions that have taken into account only integrationist political ambitions, not the ability and willingness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, the turbulence on the continent, the internal tensions in the EU can greatly affect the intensity of the situation.
And it’s hard to exclude something from the point of view of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our main political leaders are able to cope with such complicated situations.
